# AGENTS

## Do not change `go.mod` or `go.sum` unless necessary

Treat the module manifest as pinned. Do **not** edit `go.mod` or `go.sum` when building, testing, formatting, or demonstrating gobump—unless you are **intentionally** adding a new dependency or upgrading one as part of the task.

That includes:

- The `go` directive (must stay aligned with the pinned release; see `go.mod`). A `toolchain` line in a target project is ignored by gobump when bumping dependencies.
- Existing `require` versions and indirect entries

## Commands that must not be run on this repo root (without care)

| Command | Risk |
|---------|------|
| `go run .` / `make bump` | Bumps dependencies and may raise the `go` version |
| `go run . -no-git -changelog` | Same as above (still runs real `go get`) |
| `go mod tidy` / `make tidy` | Rewrites `go.mod` / `go.sum` |
| `go get` / `go get -u` | Changes versions and possibly `go` |
| `make` / `make all` | Does **not** run tidy; safe for fmt + install only |

## Safe workflow

Read the `go` line from `go.mod` (e.g. `go 1.24.12`) and pin the toolchain for every Go invocation in this tree:

```bash
export GOTOOLCHAIN=go1.24.12   # match go.mod

go test ./...
go build ./...
go fmt ./...
```

Exercise gobump against **testdata** only, never the project module:

```bash
( cd testdata/go-mod-middleware && go1.24.12 run github.com/lzap/gobump@latest -dry-run -format none )
```

Gobump sets `GOTOOLCHAIN` from the invoked `go` binary; you do not need to match a `toolchain` line in fixture `go.mod` files.

Other fixtures live under `testdata/go-mod-*` (each with its own `go.mod` and `go.sum`). Regenerate checksums after editing a fixture: `cd testdata/<case> && go mod download`.

Changelog or integration checks that need the network should use unit tests (e.g. `TestGetChangelogGolangOrgModule`), not this repository’s root `go.mod`.

## When changing `go.mod` / `go.sum` is allowed

- Adding a dependency the project actually needs
- Deliberately upgrading a library (explain in the commit)
- Intentionally bumping the pinned Go release (keep `.github/workflows/weekly-bump.yml` `go_version` in sync)

Use `GOTOOLCHAIN=go1.XX.YY` matching the `go` directive when running `go get` or `go run .` for those changes.

## Accidental edits

Restore from git:

```bash
git restore go.mod go.sum
```

See `README.md` for product behaviour; this file is only for working on the gobump source tree.
